File: Money. Heather Dowd/Flickr JOHANNESBURG - South Africa is out of the woods and no longer on a fiscal cliff based on last week's budget speech. But there is a stern warning from the Fiscal Cliff Study Group (FCSG). It said civil servants’ salaries, social grant payments and debt-service costs will soak up all government revenue. READ: SA has reached fiscal cliff: Economist It's revealed these expenses comprised 55 percent of all tax revenue in the 2007/08 financial year. This increased to 75,5 percent of tax revenue in the February 2020 budget. In order to avoid reaching the fiscal cliff as the country did last year November, the group has advised Treasury to refrain from helping non-essential and failed state-owned enterprises.